## Pavé Ring Maintenance: The Melee Stone Loss Risk

Pavé melee diamonds are held by micro-prongs or beads that are, by design, as small as possible to maximize diamond visibility. These retaining structures are subject to daily wear, impact, and prong fatigue. A micropavé stone that loosens will fall out silently — most wearers do not notice until they see a gap in the shank.

Replacement cost for a lost pavé melee stone is $200–$400 per stone depending on jeweler, location, and stone grade. An annual inspection by a qualified jeweler — where they check each stone for movement under a loupe — costs $50–$100 and catches loose stones before they are lost. This inspection is mandatory maintenance for any pavé ring, not optional.

The most durable pavé styles for daily wear are scalloped pavé (more metal around each stone) and channel-set (stones enclosed between rails). The most vulnerable are fine micropavé and French pavé on very thin shanks. Choosing platinum over gold for micropavé adds durability because platinum prongs do not wear down as quickly as 14k gold when flexed repeatedly.

## Frequently Asked Questions

### What is the difference between pavé and micropavé?
Micropavé uses the smallest available diamonds (0.8–1.0mm) set with tiny bead-prongs visible only under magnification. Standard pavé uses slightly larger stones (1.0–1.5mm) with more visible prong or bead work. Micropavé creates finer, more uniform shimmer; standard pavé creates more visible individual stone sparkle. Micropavé settings are more expensive per diamond and require more skilled labor.

### Does pavé add noticeable sparkle to an engagement ring?
Yes, but the amount depends on the pavé weight. A 1/10 ct tw micropavé shank adds subtle ambient shimmer noticeable primarily in indirect and candlelight. A 1/2–1 ct tw French pavé shank adds sparkle visible from across a room in normal indoor lighting. The center stone still dominates appearance from face-on; pavé contributes primarily from the side and in motion.

### What is a French pavé setting?
French pavé uses V-shaped cutouts between each diamond instead of round bead prongs. The V-cut removes more metal between adjacent stones, maximizing the visible diamond surface and allowing more light to enter from the sides. French pavé shows more diamond per linear centimeter of shank than any other pavé style.

### How much does a pavé engagement ring setting cost at Blue Nile?
Pavé settings at Blue Nile start at $1,200 (Petite Twist, 14k white gold, 1/10 ct. tw.) and go up to $4,550 (Star Diamond Halo Cathedral, platinum). The most popular price points are $1,200–$1,430 for simple micropavé and $2,140–$2,890 for full French pavé and Riviera Cathedral in platinum. Settings are priced separately from the center stone.

### Is pavé safe for daily wear?
Micropavé and French pavé settings carry a higher melee stone loss risk than plain solitaires or bezel settings because the retaining beads and prongs are extremely small. With annual professional inspections and avoidance of impact activities while wearing the ring, pavé holds up well for daily wear. Scalloped pavé and channel-set styles are more resistant to melee loss than pure micropavé.

### Is pavé worth the extra cost over a plain solitaire?
It depends on the budget allocation. If the center stone is already at the buyer's target grade, pavé is a meaningful visual upgrade. If the center stone budget is under 1ct and could still be improved, the pavé upgrade cost ($350–$3,000) typically delivers more visual impact as additional center stone carat weight, color, or clarity. The [Petite Twist at $1,200](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-twist-diamond-engagement-ring-in-14k-white-gold-1-10-ct-tw-item-195314?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the lowest-risk entry point — the price difference from a plain solitaire is under $400.

### What is scalloped pavé?
Scalloped pavé features curved metal cutouts between diamond positions, creating a wave or scalloped edge profile along the shank. The scallops alternate with diamond-set positions, giving the shank a textured, three-dimensional appearance compared to the flat surface of standard micropavé. Scalloped settings retain more metal around each stone than French pavé, making them slightly more secure for daily wear.

